<FIRST>r a AM-AgentsArrests     10-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agents Arrests,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Official Charges ``Witch Hunt'' By Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union official said Saturday that allegations
that Pan American World Airways ticket agents kept ticket money are
part of a ``witch hunt'' by the airline.
   Four ticket agents at Kennedy International Airport have been
charged with stealing about $1,400, said Bill Cahill, a spokesman
for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, which runs the
airport.
   ``The Port Authority and Pan Am have determined that $48,000 is
in fact missing,'' said Cahill.
   He said Port Authority detectives are investigating the four
agents and and possibly others in the disappearance of the $48,000.
   Cahill had previously indicated that the four arrested were
charged with stealing the total $48,000, but he said Saturday he
was mistaken.
   The four agents were charged Friday with falsifying records and
larceny for allegedly selling one-way tickets and keeping the cash
instead of putting the money in the register, Cahill said.
   One of the agents, Cathy Alam, is charged with taking just $38,
Cahill said.
   An official of the union that represents the agents blasted the
charges, calling it part of a scheme by Pan Am to get rid of some
union employees.
   ``I think this is just a witch hunt,'' said George Miranda, vice
president of Local 732 of the airline division of the Teamsters.
   ``I don't think these people were involved in a sophisticated
scam involving that amount of money,'' Miranda said.
   Cahill said $48,000 is missing in receipts for August and
September and that Port Authority detectives believe ticket agents
may have been keeping cash payments for about a year.
   The investigation, conducted at the request of the airline, will
continue and more arrests are expected, Cahill said.
   A Pan Am spokesman didn't immediately respond to a telephone
request for comment.
</TEXT>
