<FIRST>r a BC-Keating-Babbitt     10-15 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Keating-Babbitt,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Babbitt Says Keating Called for Aid in 1985</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Bruce Babbitt said Saturday that
American Continental Corp. Chairman Charles H. Keating Jr.
contacted him in 1985 to ask him to intercede on Keating's behalf
against the nation's top thrift regulator.
   ``Keating called me and said, `Edwin Gray (then chairman of the
Federal Home Loan Bank Board) is getting on my back ... I want you
to intervene,''' Babbitt said. ``I refused.''
   Keating declined to comment on the matter involving Lincoln
Savings and Loan Association of Irvine, Calif., an American
Continental subsidiary that was at the time at odds with the Bank
Board.
   Babbitt, who left office early in 1987 to seek the Democratic
nomination for president, said Keating called only once. He said he
was unaware at the time that other Arizona politicians had received
similar requests from Keating.
   Babbitt made his remarks to about 100 people at a Phoenix
meeting sponsored by the citizens lobby Common Cause.
   American Continental filed for federal bankruptcy protection
April 13, and the government took over Lincoln the next day.
   The thrift's failure, which regulators blame in part on risky
ventures, eventually could cost taxpayers $1.1 billion to $2.5
billion.
   In 1985, Gray and Keating were battling over Gray's support for
a regulation that put strict limits on the amount of assets thrifts
were allowed to invest directly in real estate, securities and
other risky ventures without regulators' approval.
   Babbitt said he received one political contribution from Keating
in 1982 but none during his presidential candidacy.
</TEXT>
