<SECOND>BC-Britain-Waite,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Assured Terry Waite is Alive</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Church of England said Sunday it has been
assured by a reliable Iranian informant that missing church envoy
Terry Waite is alive on his 1,000th day in captivity.
   The unidentified source also provided assurances that two other
Britons missing in Lebanon, journalist John McCarthy and Northern
Irish teacher Brian Keenan, are alive, said Eve Keatley, a
spokeswoman for Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie.
   Waite, 50, the archbishop's personal emissary, vanished in
Beirut on Jan. 20, 1987, while trying to negotiate the release of
two U.S. hostages. He was on his fifth mission to Lebanon, and is
widely believed to have been taken captive by Iranian-backed Shiite
Moslem extremists.
   ``We have had further assurances this weekend from Iranian
sources that the three British hostages are alive,'' Ms. Keatley
said.
   ``We still have no concrete proof of this,'' she said. ``The
information comes via a channel that we think is reliable but which
we do not wish to identify.''
   A prayer by the archbishop was being said Sunday at churches
across Britain.
   ``Give Terry a sense of your abiding presence and the assurance
that fellow believers are one with him in spirit; encourage him and
all other hostages to face each new day in confidence and hope; and
grant that they may soon be restored to those whom they love,'' it
said.
   On Sunday, McCarthy had been missing for 1,278 days and Keenan
for 1,283 days.
   No group has claimed to hold them or Waite and there have been
no photographs or videotapes to prove they are alive. The British
government says no demands have been made for their freedom.
   Thirteen other Westerners, including eight Americans, are
missing. All Americans are believed held by Shiite factions.
   The longest held hostage is American Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. He was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
