<FIRST>r a BC-AmmoniaLeak     10-15 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ammonia Leak,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Allowed To Return Home After Ammonia Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLSTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the 6,500 residents forced to flee
when a frozen pizza plant leaked deadly ammonia gas were allowed
back into their homes early Sunday, but people with breathing
problems were told to wait.
   Authorities ordered a complete evacuation of the town Saturday
night when the gas, used for refrigeration, began leaking and
spread quickly over an area of about half a mile, said Fire
Department Lt. Ron Winters.
   Twenty-four people affected by the gas were taken to hospitals
and four were admitted, officials said. Many others were given
oxygen by paramedics who rushed to the scene from around the
largely rural southeastern quarter of Ohio.
   The anhydrous ammonia leak at the Pillsbury Co. Jeno's plant was
brought under control by 10:55 p.m., said Mayor John Carey.
   Assistant Fire Chief Bob Long said people started returning to
their homes just after 5 a.m. Sunday.
   ``The fog is still heavy. It's starting to lift up a little and
it smells kind of funny. You get a little odor of it,'' Long said.
   The mayor warned that the elderly, people with breathing
problems and small children could be affected by remaining vapor
and should remain away from the town until the ammonia dissipated
completely.
   Police had ordered people to evacuate a seven-block area near
the plant, then expanded the order to cover the entire town as the
gas spread, said Highway Patrol Dispatcher Jack Riley.
   Sheriff's deputies went door-to-door ordering people out of
their homes.
   Resident Vicki Dailey said she, her husband and two children
fled choking fumes about 9 p.m.
   ``We were out in the driveway and at first could not smell
anything,'' Mrs. Dailey said. ``But within about two minutes, we
started smelling it and decided to get out. We were choking.''
   Repair crews working breathing bottled oxygen reported the leak
came from a ruptured 16-inch pipe, but the cause of the break
wasn't known, said Vinton County Deputy Sheriff Marc Smith.
   Anhydrous ammonia fumes can be fatal if inhaled, according to an
emergency guidebook by the U.S. Department of Transportation.
   Calls to the plant were not answered Sunday morning.
</TEXT>
