<DOCNO> AP891015-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     10-15 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Condemns Modern Influences, Says They Endanger Families</HEAD>
<HEAD>By LAURINDA KEYS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORT LOUIS, Mauritius (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II said Sunday that
technological advancements such as television are threatening
traditional family life on this Indian Ocean island nation.
   ``Modern life has reached the shores of the island. Asphalt
roads and electricity arrive the same time as the means of social
communication'' such as television and videos, the pope told a
stadium full of Roman Catholics on the tiny island of Rodrigues,
390 miles east of the main island of Mauritius.
   ``In itself, this is praiseworthy progress, but, as in other
societies, Rodrigues suffers in full from influences such as those
of the video that threaten stability in the family,'' the pontiff
said.
   The 36,500 French-speaking inhabitants of Rodrigues are mainly
African-descended farmers and farm workers. About 97 percent are
Catholic.
   The pope expressed concern about the growing number of islanders
leaving to seek jobs in the booming economy on the main island,
where he arrived Saturday after eight days in Korea and Indonesia.
He returns to Rome on Monday.
   ``For a long time, Rodrigues seemed to be living tranquilly as
one big united family in which everyone knew everyone else and no
one was an outcast,'' said the pope. ``And suddenly, there is worry
about the future.''
   He urged the islanders to safeguard traditional values in a
country where tourism has doubled in the past six years to about
200,000 annually. Cardinal Jean Margeot has warned that the influx
of outsiders is creating serious ``moral'' problems for Mauritians.
   As the pope toured the island, topless European and South
African women sunned themselves on beaches in a land where most
native women wear long dresses and don't smoke or drink alcohol.
   In the past six years, 90,000 jobs have been created on
Mauritius, a democracy where people of several races and religions
coexist peacefully.
   The government of Prime Minister Anerood Jugnauth has actively
courted foreign investment, creating a special export zone to
diversify the economy from its centuries of dependence on sugarcane.
   But Mauritians have become concerned about pollution as factory
smoke begins to cloud the sharp-edged mountains around the lagoons
and gas stations appear alongside the palm trees.
   The government last year created a department to monitor the
quality of life and financed it from liquor and cigarette taxes.
   Mauritius also has become a transit point for drug smugglers.
Signs at the international airport warn of a death penalty for
trafficking in narcotics.
</TEXT>
