<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     10-15 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Condemns Arrest of Invaders of U.S. Ambassador's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea on Sunday denounced the
arrests of six students who stormed the U.S. ambassador's residence
in rival South Korea last week.
   The official government newspaper Minju Choson declared: ``The
action of the Seoul students was an eruption of towering
indignation at the U.S. imperialist aggressors who have established
a colonial fascist rule over South Korea.''
   On Friday, six students stormed the official residence of U.S.
Ambassador Donald Gregg in Seoul. They hurled homemade bombs and
smashed artwork with iron bars, but Gregg and his wife, Meg,
escaped unharmed through a side entrance.
   Minju Choson's commentary, broadcast by the North's Korean
Central News Agency, said the arrest of the students ``is a
repressive outrage which could be done only by the pro-U.S.
flunky-ist traitors who cannot live a day without the patronage of
the U.S. imperialists.''
   It added: ``The Seoul students took over the U.S. ambassador's
residence and held an anti-U.S. sit-in, strongly demanding a
negotiation with the ambassador, a CIA agent, cancellation of the
traitor Roh Tae-woo's planned trip to the United states and stop to
the U.S. pressure on South Korea to import its agricultural and
aquatic products.
   ``This was an entirely just act,'' the newspaper said.
   Roh, the South Korean president, left Sunday for the United
States to confer with President Bush and address a joint session of
Congress.
   Gregg was a CIA station chief in Seoul in the 1970s.
   Radical students in South Korea oppose the presence of 43,000
U.S. military troops, stationed there under a mutual defense pact,
saying they hamper reunification of the Korean Peninsula.
   The peninsula has been divided since 1945 into the Communist
North and capitalist South.
</TEXT>
