<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-WallBomber     10-15 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Bomber,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Saves Old Mural of B-17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While World War II still raged, an American
serviceman had a burst of inspiration and painted a giant picture
of the famed B-17 bomber on a brick wall at a U.S. airfield.
   The B-17 is ancient aviation history now, and the airfield is
used as a drag-racing strip. The name of the fatigue-clad artist is
barely remembered.
   But the mural that stood in obscurity since 1944 has been taken
down as part of a plan to restore it and move it to a permanent
place of honor.
   ``It was a thrill to see something that has been in the dark for
more than 40 years come into the light again and be saved for
posterity,'' said Richard Nimmo, one of a group of English
enthusiasts who seek to perserve such relics.
   The picture _ which shows the famous ``Flying Fortress''
unloading its bombs while anti-aircraft shells burst around it _
was taken down Saturday from its place at Podington airfield, an
old base of the World War II-era U.S. 8th Air Force.
   Podington airfield, 65 miles north of London, was one of about
130 8th Air Force bases for bombers and fighters in the eastern
England flatlands. They were established to raid Germany and
German-occupied territory.
   After the war, most of the Podington field reverted to farming.
The brick huts used by the crews have remained as workshops for
drag-racing on the airfield runway, and the control tower has been
converted into a house.
   The mural was on a piece of wall on farmland. The removal team
had to get permission from the farmer to take down the painting,
and they will have to rebuild the wall. A benefactor has given them
750 red bricks for the task.
   With help from the U.S. air base at Alconbury near Cambridge,
the mural is to soon be transported to Duxford, another old 8th Air
Force field about 35 miles east of Podington.
   Britain's Imperial War Museum maintains Duxford for its
collection of historic aircraft and will set up the B-17 mural as
part of its display about the 8th Air Force.
   The 12-by-8 foot painting was done in about 1944 by a staff
sergeant named Walderschmidt, Nimmo said.
   ``We think he was on the ground crew,'' he said. ``We don't know
anything else about him except that we heard he is still alive in
the United States. We don't know his first name or where he lives.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
