<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e AM-Opera 1stLd-Writethru a0682 10-15 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0682,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alessandra Marc Makes Debut in `Aida'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf pvs, `The rest ...' to CORRECT Radames to hero
sted heroine.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just a few years ago, opera audiences and
critics were bemoaning the lack of any new Verdi sopranos to fill
the void left by the retirement of Leontyne Price.
   Then came a young American upstart named Aprile Millo.
   On Saturday came another _ Alessandra Marc.
   Even in a Metropolitan Opera season notable for exciting debuts,
Marc's first performance as ``Aida'' was something special, as the
standing-room-only crowd acknowledged with its repeated ovations.
   Here is the genuine article _ a dramatic soprano with an opulent
voice that can be thrilling in its power or tender in its warmth as
the occasion demands.
   She has the gleaming tones to ride above the full forces of
orchestra and chorus that Verdi assembled for the Triumphal Scene
of Act 2. She has the artistry to create a portrayal of the
tormented Ethiopian princess in the aria ``O patria mia,'' which
opens the Nile Scene in Act 3.
   She also has a few problems.
   Vocally, the lower register of her voice is undeveloped and
colorless. At the other end of her range, she has trouble reining
in the volume and seems unable to float the high pianissimos that
are one of Millo's trademarks.
   Dramatically, Marc is hampered by being enormously overweight, a
condition that makes believable involvement with the other
characters difficult. In one of the opera's most moving scenes, her
father, Amonasro, is supposed to throw Aida to the ground in angry
rejection. The most that baritone Juan Pons could do was push her
gently and allow her to slump on a nearby rock.
   Marc, who is in her early 30s, grew up in the Washington, D.C.,
area, as Judith Borden. She changed her name a few years ago,
saying she was tired of being confused with the soprano Judith
Blegen and wanted a name with a good international ring to it.
   She has the name. Now it's up to her whether she will have the
career to match.
   The rest of Saturday's ``Aida'' was workmanlike but
undistinguished. As the wooden hero, Radames, tenor Nicola
Martinucci strained at his high notes; mezzo Stefania Toczyska was
earnest, if not thrilling, as the villainous Amneris, and Pons
brought warmth and intensity to the brief role of Amonasro.
Christian Badea's conducting was lively and sensitive.
   Marc is the second American singer to make a triumphant debut
this season at the Met, a company often criticized for being too
slow to engage promising native talent. Two weeks ago, tenor
Richard Leech sang Rodolfo in Puccini's ``La Boheme'' to great
acclaim. Millo, who has been singing major roles at the Met for
several years, got to open the current season as ``Aida.''
   There's more to come. The coloratura June Anderson will debut in
Verdi's ``Rigoletto'' later this fall; Susan Dunn, another
contender in the Verdi sweepstakes, sings in ``Il Trovatore'' in
February, and soprano Ashley Putnam will sing in Gounod's ``Faust''
in March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891015-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica-Profiles     10-15 0972</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Profiles,1006</SECOND>
<HEAD>Profiles of Eight Freed Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are profiles of the eight
South African political prisoners freed Sunday. Five were tried and
sentenced in 1964, along with Nelson Mandela, to life in prison for
sabotage and conspiracy in a trial in the Johannesburg suburb of
Rivonia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WALTER SISULU:
   Sisulu ran day-to-day operations of the ANC as secretary-general
from 1949-54, when the government ordered him to resign. He was one
of the ANC's most important leaders in the years when it grew from
a small organization into a mass movement. He helped organize a
national campaign to defy apartheid laws in 1952.
   Born May 18, 1912, in the Xhosa homeland of Transkei, he joined
the congress in 1940 and formed the Youth League in 1943 to press
for more aggressive tactics. After his acquittal along with 155
other defendants in a 1956-61 treason trial, Sisulu was restricted
to his house, arrested six times, and finally convicted of
furthering the aims of the now-outlawed guerrilla group. While on
bail pending appeal he went underground and was captured three
months later in Rivonia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AHMED KATHRADA:
   Kathrada, arrested at age 17 for participation in a passive
resistance campaign in 1946, was a member of the high command of
the African National Congress' military wing. He is one of only two
Rivonia defendants who denied all the charges against him. He was
convicted on only one count, sabotage.
   Kathrada was born Aug. 21, 1929, in the western Transvaal to a
scholarly Moslem family and became involved in politics at age 11.
He joined the Communist Party in the early 1940s and as general
secretary of the Transvaal Indian Congress was instrumental in
linking it to the African National Congress. He was acquitted in
the 1956-61 mass treason trial but placed under house arrest in
1962. He went underground a few months before his arrest at Rivonia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ELIAS MOTSOALEDI:
   As a founder of the Johannesburg regional command of the ANC's
military wing, Motsoaledi hid recruits and helped send them abroad
for military training and procuring arms, prosecutors alleged at
the Rivonia trial. He said he joined the military wing in 1962.
   Born in northern Transvaal Province on July 26, 1924, the son of
a migrant laborer, Motsoaledi worked in Johannesburg as a servant
and at factories. He joined the Communist Party in 1949 and the
congress in 1948.
   In 1949, he became chairman of the Council of Non-European Trade
Unions, organized strikes and was banned in 1952. He was held in
solitary confinement for three months in 1960 before going
underground. His wife, Caroline, lives in Soweto. Three of their
seven children are in exile.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   RAYMOND MHLABA:
   At the Rivonia trial, Mhlaba denied he belonged to the high
command of the African National Congress' military wing. But he was
identified in the South African press as the man who became
commander-in-chief after the arrest in 1962 of Mandela.
   In 1952, Mhlaba was the first congress leader arrested as part
of the defiance campaign, when he led blacks through the ``whites
only'' entrance to a train station.
   He was born Dec. 2, 1920, son of a policeman. He dropped out of
school, became active in trade unions in Port Elizabeth, joined the
Communist Party in 1943 and the congress in 1944.
   In 1986, prison authorities allowed him to marry the mother of
three of his eight children.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ANDREW MLANGENI:
   Mlangeni said at the Rivonia trial he had agreed to carry
messages for the congress' military wing, but he denied he was a
member. He was accused during the trial of being responsible for
explosives and being a member of the Johannesburg command.
   Born in Johannesburg on May 30, 1926, he worked as a golf caddy
to pay for school and later as a clerk, bus driver and journalist.
He joined the congress in 1951 and was regional secretary for the
township of Soweto from 1958-60, before he went underground.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WILTON MKWAYI:
   Mkwayi, 66, briefly took command of the congress' military wing
after the arrest of Mandela's colleagues in 1963. He was arrested
shortly afterward and sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 after
being convicted on 58 counts of sabotage. The judge said Mkwayi
received guerrilla training in China and had taught African
National Congress members how to make bombs. In 1987, Mkwayi was
allowed to marry his common-law wife, Irene. She died in December.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   JAFTA MASEMULA:
   Masemula, 58, a member of the outlawed Pan Africanist Congress
guerrilla organization, was sentenced to life in prison in 1963 for
sabotage. At the time of his arrest in 1961, he was a primary
school teacher in Atteridgeville, near Pretoria. Some other members
of the Pan Africanist Congress were freed last year after agreeing
to a government offer of release in exchange for renunciation of
violence. Masemula refused to do so.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   OSCAR MPETHA:
   The country's oldest political prisoner, 80-year-old Mpetha
began campaigning for black rights as a union organizer in the
1940s. A diabetic, he had a leg amputated in 1983 and been
hospitalized for most of the past three years.
   Born Aug. 5, 1909, he joined the African National Congress in
1951 and became its Cape Town regional chairman in 1958. He helped
found the Communist-oriented South African Congress of Trade Unions.
   In 1980, he was charged with murder and terrorism in connection
with the slaying of two whites at a roadblock erected by black
youths near Cape Town. He was convicted of terrorism in 1983 and
began a five-year sentence in 1985 after losing an appeal.
   In August 1983, Mpetha was elected co-president of the United
Democratic Front, a nationwide anti-apartheid coalition.
   Mpetha's wife and a son died while he was jailed. He was denied
permission to attend the funerals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891015-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-TinyTransplant     10-15 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tiny Transplant,0179</SECOND>
<UNK>Surgeons Give 39-Day-Old Girl New Heart</UNK>
<DATELINE>PADOVA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors said Sunday that a 39-day-old
Italian girl who underwent a heart transplant operation was in
stable condition and resting peacefully.
   Giorgia Panizzolo, who was born Sept. 5 with a tumor in her
heart, became the youngest person to undergo the surgery in Italy
when doctors at Padova Hospital completed the four-hour operation
early Saturday.
   Dr. Vincenzo Gallucci, who headed the surgical team, said the
girl would have survived without the operation and was near death
when the surgery began late Friday.
   The surgeon also said the girl could have a better chance for a
healthy life than someone who had the surgery as an adult.
   ``At this age there is no risk of rejection because the body has
not yet developed antibodies,'' he explained.
   The hospital said the donor was a 3-month-old West German girl
who died Friday in Freiburg of a cerebral anuerism.
   The Italian girl is the daughter of Antonio Pannizzolo, a
28-year-old farmer, and his wife Sonia, 23.
</TEXT>
