<FIRST>r w AM-DoomsdayProject     10-15 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Doomsday Project,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whistle Blower Claims Harassment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top secret government program known as the
Doomsday Project is leaving a bitter legacy, with a veteran
counterintelligence expert alleging he is being harassed for
reporting improprieties and poor management.
   The program, referred to at the Pentagon simply as Project 908,
is designed to ensure that even if top U.S. civilian leaders are
killed in a surprise nuclear attack, the United States can still
unleash its own atomic weapons on the Soviet Union.
   So far, the government has spent $4 billion to $5 billion to
build supply depots, underground bunkers and a communications
network that has been plagued with problems, say Pentagon sources,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Army inspector general's office reviewed the program in 1987
and interviewed Army civilian employee W. Thomas Golden.
   Golden, chief of the operations security branch at the
Information Systems Command in Fort Huachuca, Ariz., asserted to
the IG that:
   _The communications network vital to the project didn't work
properly, was costing hundreds of millions of dollars to fix and
Project 908 officials on several occasions misled members of
Congress into believing that the system was operational when in
fact it wasn't.
   _The son of Army Brig. Gen. Eugene Renzi was doing work for
Betac Corp., an Arlington, Va., firm to which Renzi had directed a
sole-source, no-bid contract in connection with Project 908.
   _The Betac contract specified that one of Renzi's aides would be
a $400-a-day consultant to the company.
   Army regulations say the inspector general will protect the
anonymity of witnesses, but within weeks of Golden's confidential
discussions, word had leaked to Renzi that Golden was making
allegations against the general.
   Golden alleged that Col. Ned Bacheldor, chief of the inspector
general's intelligence oversight division, had informed Renzi that
Golden was the source of the allegation about Renzi's son. Renzi
told Army investigators in sworn testimony he had found out about
Golden's allegations from an aide, not from Bacheldor.
   The Army inspector general's office concluded that Renzi had
retaliated against Golden by spreading word that Golden would not
be welcome at Fort Ritchie, Md., where Renzi directed the 7th
Signal Command.
   ``Because of ... Renzi's action,'' Golden's effectiveness ``was
diminished'' and ``he could not do his job,'' according to an Army
memo obtained by The Associated Press.
   Golden requested reassignment and now handles
counterintelligence matters in connection with the Strategic
Defense Initiative.
   Renzi was reprimanded for retaliating against Golden, but has
since been promoted to the rank of major general and is stationed
in Hawaii.
   Renzi, Bacheldor and Golden all rejected interview requests made
through military spokesmen.
   But the AP has learned that Renzi told a House Armed Services
Committee investigator late last year that Bacheldor had leaked
Golden's name to Renzi's boss, Lt. Gen. Emmett Paige, who passed it
along to Renzi.
   Golden told Congress recently he still is being targeted for
retribution. Two officials in Project 908 ``have engaged in a smear
campaign against me,'' Golden said in a letter to the House Armed
Services Committee obtained by The AP from sources on Capitol Hill.
   Security chief John Hartford and legal counsel Ernie Peluso
tried to obtain Golden's telephone records in an effort to link him
to a reporter for U.S. News &amp; World Report who wrote an article
about Project 908, Golden alleged.
   Hartford and Peluso work at the Defense Mobilization Systems
Planning Activity, a key Project 908 component where Bacheldor is
now chief of staff.
   According to several sources, Army Secretary John Marsh
intervened and stopped the effort to get Golden's telephone records.
   Hartford and Peluso declined requests for interviews to comment
on the reports.
   Renzi's son and the $400-a-day consultant who was Renzi's aide
left the Betac payroll early in 1988, according to Pentagon sources.
   The work Betac does for the government is ``aboveboard, there's
been no wrongdoing by Betac'' and ``this is all water over the
dam,'' said Joseph Royal, the company's director of personnel.
</TEXT>
