<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     10-15 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0136</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Guerrillas, Two Soldiers Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separate clashes in the southeast
provinces of Siirt and Hakkari killed seven Kurdish guerrillas and
two soldiers, the regional governor's office announced Sunday.
   The announcement, carried by the Anatolia news agency, said the
seven rebels were killed in a shootout near the village of Damlarca
village in Eruh township on Sunday.
   It said security forces captured another guerrilla and seized
automatic guns, hand grenades and outlawed publications after the
clash.
   A lieutenant and a private were killed in a shootout near the
Iraqi border on Saturday night, the announcement said.
   Kurdish guerrillas are fighting for an independent state in the
southeast. They belong to the outlawed Kurdish Labor Party, a
Marxist group with headquarters in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa
Valley in Lebanon.
