<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1327EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietMilitary     10-15 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Military,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Report Finds Little Cutback Within U.S.S.R.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is on schedule in withdrawing
forces from Eastern Europe but has made little progress on military
reductions within its borders, says a congressional report released
Sunday.
   The House Armed Services Committee study found that since late
April the Soviets have been pulling back their forces as part of
reductions proposed by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Dec. 7,
1988.
   However, the withdrawal of six tank divisions, 50,000 men and
5,000 tanks from Eastern Europe has not been carried out as Western
observers expected.
   ``Rather than withdrawing a tank division in its entirety, the
motorized rifle regiment assigned to it is being transferred to a
division that would remain in Eastern Europe and a tank regiment
from that division withdrawn instead,'' the report said.
   A motorized rifle regiment is similar to a U.S. mechanized
infantry.
   Thirteen members of the committee traveled to the Soviet Union
in early August, a 13-day trip that included visits to an East
German military unit, a motorized rifle division in Yavorov and an
intermediate-range nuclear forces elimination facility in Sarny.
   The report was based on observations by the legislators and
defense experts who traveled with the delegation.
   The committee's assessment is consistent with comments made by
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney last month in releasing the Pentagon
study, ``Soviet Military Power.''
   Cheney said that while the Soviets are unilaterally withdrawing
some ground forces, they are reorganizing and modernizing their
general purpose forces, upgrading their communications networks and
researching future generations of weapons systems.
   The congressional report said there is ``great uncertainty about
what the Soviets will do with the equipment being removed from
their forces.'' Specifically, the study found that tanks withdrawn
from Eastern Europe and slated to be destroyed or converted, will
likely replace older equipment in units within the Soviet Union.
   The study concluded that ``Soviet forces are clearly being
pulled back from Eastern Europe into the Soviet Union, but little
is known so far about what is happening to Soviet forces inside the
Soviet Union.''
   Gorbachev had vowed to reduce Soviet forces west of the Ural
mountains by 10,000 tanks, 8,500 artillery pieces and 800 combat
aircraft. The timetable for the reductions and withdrawals is two
years.
   Based on observations of its members, the committee concluded
that ``while NATO must be careful to avoid taking any actions that
are more difficult to reverse than those happening on the other
side, it is not too soon to take advantage of the changes already
taking place on the ground, namely the withdrawal of Soviet forces
from Eastern Europe.''
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., the chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee who headed the delegation, said, ``Now that we have a
good understanding of what's going on there, we can figure out how
to respond.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
