<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1341EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Choice-Hawkins     10-15 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Choice-Hawkins,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hawkins Criticizes Choice Hearings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Education Department is expanding the
scope of its regional strategy sessions to include initiatives
beyond ``choice,'' after months of wrangling with the chairman of
the House Education Committee about the meetings' limited agenda.
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos opens the first session Monday
night, when he meets with East Harlem, N.Y., parents. A daylong
session, complete with a plenary and concurrent workshops, will
follow on Tuesday.
   ``Our purpose in calling for these meetings is to ratchet up the
debate about the importance of choice in the move to restructure
schools,'' said Education Undersecretary John Sanders.
   Choice is the concept that allows parents to decide where their
children will attend school. It is based on the theory that
competition will shake up and improve bad schools.
   However, Rep. Augustus Hawkins, chairman of the House Education
and Labor Committee, had argued that the Education Department's
strategy sessions should address other proposals for education
reform.
   Hawkins said he and several committee members object to
``choice'' because ``we believe it's a new way of resegregating the
schools.'' He added that some disadvantaged children also may be
forced to give up needed services in order to attend a school
outside the district.
   He said the department has relented and that the meetings will
include other ideas and that opponents of ``choice'' will be
allowed to talk.
   Hawkins, D-Calif., bristles at the cross-country ``choice''
blitz that will take the education secretary to Minnesota, North
Carolina, Colorado and California over the next two months.
   ``Why have they selected one program in education, which is not
authorized (by Congress) and not included in the package that we
passed last year?'' said Hawkins, pointing to an outline of the
``School Improvement'' Act.
   The new law reauthorizes virtually all major federal elementary
and secondary education programs through fiscal year 1993,
including Chapter One for the disadvantaged, science and math
programs, magnet programs for specialized instruction, bilingual
education and child development.
   Hawkins said the new law ``provided for some accountability at
school districts to document improvements over each year,'' as well
as local control.
   ``Full funding and implementation of the School Improvement Act
of 1988 assures precisely that kind of choice, and I urge you to
make it your most immediate and top priority,'' said Hawkins in a
letter to Cavazos.
   ``Real choice comes about when all parents get involved on a
daily basis with the education of their children, whether they
attend magnet schools or not,'' said the letter. ``Administrators,
teachers, parents and their children working together for school
improvements in each school building, as required in the Chapter
One (for disadvantaged children), for instance, will help to bring
about improvements for all children, not just those who attend
certain select schools.''
   Sanders acknowledged that the new law ``addresses accountability
and local control, yes,'' but stressed that ``it deals specifically
with federal programs. It gives new accountability measures within
those programs. We're talking about (something) much broader. We're
talking about the system itself.''
   Since he could not stop the meetings, Hawkins said he worked for
months before he got the Education Department to agree to allow
other education reform programs to be discussed and opponents of
``choice'' to participate.
   Hawkins also received an invitation to attend but it was
uncertain whether he would.
   Reps. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., and Steve Bartlett, R-Texas, are
expected to attend, along with participants from Maine, Vermont,
New Hampshire, Connecticut, Massachusetts, Rhode Island, New York,
New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, West Virginia,
District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
   Cavazos and New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean will address the meeting.
   The most controversial form of school choice is allowing parents
to send their child to a school outside their school district. But
other initiatives include magnet schools that specialize in certain
subjects, alternative programs and teacher-initiated schools.
   So far this year, Arkansas, Iowa, and Nebraska have joined
Minnesota, whose open enrollment plan went into effect this past
school year. Many other states offer more limited choice options
aimed at gifted students or youngsters with academic problems that
only certain districts can handle.
   Chapter One is given to schools that have a large concentration
of disadvantage students and are located in low-income areas.
   Expected high transportation costs also will limited the options
of low-income parents, Hawkins said.
</TEXT>
