<FIRST>r i AM-Cyprus-Refugees     10-15 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cyprus-Refugees,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Troops Block Greek Cypriots Trying to Go Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASTROMERITIS, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sobbing refugees and their children
scuffled with U.N. troops Sunday who blocked them from returning to
Turkish-occupied northern Cyprus from the Greek sector of the
divided island.
   Police estimated the number of demonstrators at 3,000 and
stopped most of them from bursting into the U.N.-patrolled buffer
zone splitting Cyprus into Greek and Turkish sectors.
   But about 200 demonstrators, mainly women and children, managed
to push through lines of police and British and Danish U.N.
peacekeeping troops.
   After repeated scuffles, they broke through the three successive
lines to penetrate about 500 yards into the buffer zone. They were
stopped before reaching the fortified Turkish lines, about 500
yards away.
   ``We ask you not to proceed further as we cannot guarantee your
safety,'' a U.N. officer repeatedly said through a bullhorn.
   Some troops roughly pushed back the refugees. Others chased
children and young teen-age boys and girls, bringing some of them
down with flying tackles.
   Armed Turkish troops and Turkish Cypriot riot police stood on
the outskirts of the village on the far edge of the buffer zone.
   ``That's my home over there, you have no right to stop me,''
17-year-old Niki Avraamidou shouted, exhausted after trying
repeatedly to push through a line of U.N. troops.
   Erene Figuri, 60, holding her 9-year-old grandson Tofis by the
hand, argued angrily with Danish peacekeepers. Tofis slipped
through the cordon several times while the soldiers were scuffling
with older people, only to be chased and brought back each time.
   Other demonstrators sat at the edge of the buffer zone, singing
religious hymns and songs of yearning about their lost homes and
waving Greek and Cypriot flags and banners.
   ``Our right to return is not negotiable,'' said one huge cloth
banner.
   A series of U.N. resolutions on Cyprus call for the return of
the 200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees expelled from their homes after
the Turkish invasion of 1974.
   The resolutions also demand the withdrawal of the 30,000 Turkish
troops and 35,000-50,000 Turkish mainland settlers brought to
northern Cyprus.
   The Turkish Cypriot leadership rejects the right of any of the
Greek Cypriot refugees to return. The buffer zone, which splits the
island, effectively prevents any contact between the two sides.
   It was the fourth attempt this year by Greek Cypriot refugees to
walk back to their homes.
   On two of the earlier attempts, refugees were beaten by Turkish
Cypriot police, arrested and jailed for ``illegal entry'' into the
breakaway Turkish Cypriot state, which was proclaimed unilaterally
in 1983 and has only been recognized by Turkey.
   U.N.-sponsored peace talks between President George Vassiliou,
the Greek Cypriot leader, and Rauf Denktash, the president of the
breakaway state, have been deadlocked since June.
</TEXT>
