<FIRST>r i AM-Refugees     10-15 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germans Wait to Travel West, Others Escape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds more East Germans flocked to the
West German Embassy here over the weekend, bringing to more than
1,200 the number expected to leave for the West beginning Monday.
   The exodus also gained strength elsewhere. More than 2,100 East
Germans made their to West Germany over the weekend by escaping
through Hungary, which opened its western border to refugees Sept.
10.
   At the West German Embassy on a tree-lined street in Warsaw,
200-300 new refugees arrived over the weekend, diplomatic sources
said. That brought the total to more than 1,200.
   East German Trabant cars lined the street in front of the
embassy, and Poles continued to buy them at a brisk pace _ handing
cash to the refugees, taking the keys and driving off.
   East Germans were seen arriving throughout the day. In the
afternoon a group of refugees in the embassy compound were moved to
temporary shelter elsewhere.
   In a decision announced Saturday by the Polish state news agency
PAP, East Germany said the refugees will be allowed to obtain exit
documents in Warsaw and then travel directly to any country they
choose.
   It appeared that arrangements for the departure from Poland were
still being made Sunday. A West German official in Bonn said the
first departures could come Monday.
   Refugees said they were told West Germany was arranging
transport for them either by plane or ferry.
   Those arriving at the Warsaw embassy Sunday included a family
that persuaded East German authorities to let them travel to Poland
by presenting a holiday invitation from a Polish family.
   The father said he decided to leave because of the fierce police
crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrations that swept East Germany
during ceremonies marking the 40th anniversary of the country's
founding Oct. 7.
   The man said he was shocked by the repression.
   ``My protest was to leave,'' he said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Other refugees also cited police brutality as the trigger for
their flight from their homeland.
   Despite tighter restrictions imposed on East German travel
abroad in the wake of the refugee flood, hundreds escape daily and
make their way either to West Germany's embassies in Eastern Europe
or to Hungary.
   More than 52,000 East Germans have flooded into West Germany
since Sept. 10, and another 70,000 more have been allowed to
emigrate legally so far this year.
</TEXT>
