<FIRST>r a AM-HastingsWaits     10-15 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings Waits,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeached Judge Awaits Verdict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After eight years, final Senate hearings on the
impeachment case against U.S. District Judge Alcee L. Hastings are
tentatively set for this week, with a vote on whether to remove him
from office possible by week's end.
   Removal from the bench would be a form of ``living death,'' said
Hastings, who was acquitted in a jury trial, but he's anxious to
move ahead with his life.
   ``We are now talking in the ninth year of this matter,'' he said
in an interview. ``Everyone should be entitled to closure by now.
It's not in the best interests of Al Hastings (and) it does not
serve the community.''
   He noted the busy Southern District of Florida has been, in
effect, one judge short. He stopped hearing criminal cases last
year and hasn't presided in a civil trial since early summer, when
he was preparing for the inquiry by a special 12-member Senate
panel.
   A vote by two-thirds of the full Senate would be needed to
remove him from his $89,500-a-year job.
   He's ready to return to the bench ``with vigor,'' Hastings said,
or to begin a new job he refused to give any hints about.
   ``I have a plan to stay and a plan to go,'' said Hastings, 52,
appointed in 1979 by President Carter as Florida's first black
federal judge. ``I believe everyone knows that the system will not
cause me to roll over.''
   His problems began Oct. 9, 1981, when his friend William A.
Borders, a Washington attorney, was arrested in an undercover FBI
operation of alleged fixing of court cases. Borders was convicted
of bribery conspiracy, but Hastings was acquitted in a separate
1983 jury trial.
   However, a subsequent investigation led to Hastings' impeachment
last year in the House, which accused him of plotting to obtain a
bribe, lying during his trial defense and an unrelated charge of
disclosing federal wiretap information.
   Hastings said he thinks he has ``a good shot'' of remaining on
the bench.
   However, some senators expressed doubts about some of Hastings'
actions. Among those: his showing up at a restaurant, as Borders
had told an undercover agent Hastings would do, to signify Borders'
influence with him, and his efforts to avoid FBI agents in
Washington the night of Borders' arrest.
   Hastings said the Senate inquiry produced no ``smoking gun,'' no
strong new evidence against him.
   ``In fairness to anybody who is a detractor of mine, you could
say there is some persuasive evidence that one could infer that I
was guilty. But persuasive evidence has to be conclusive before you
pull that switch.''
   Hastings is the only federal official ever impeached after
acquittal in a trial and his attorneys argued for years that he was
being subjected to unconstitutional double jeopardy.
   ``You have to know that I'm the only person in America this has
happened to,'' he said.
   He continues to protest the use of a Senate panel, instead of
the full Senate, to hear his case. The panel then sent a report to
the other senators. The Senate, which says it's free to handle its
business as it sees fit, has in recent years used the panel system
to keep other Senate business from being halted by impeachment
cases.
   In recent months, Hastings has made speeches in 10 states and
dozens of Florida cities, explaining his case and urging people to
write their senators. Ken Klein, spokesman for Sen. Bob Graham,
D-Fla., said Graham's office has answered 1,400 letters, most in
Hastings' support.
   ``It has been difficult,'' Hastings said. ``But if it is next
week or next month, when the dust settles, I will be standing tall
with dignity.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
