<FIRST>r w AM-Budget     10-15 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Darman Says Automatic Budget Cuts Would Be Good Medicine For Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House budget chief said Sunday it
might be best if Congress leaves in place automatic spending cuts
that take effect Monday night rather than follow the past practice
of rolling them back.
   The $16 billion cut, formally known as a sequestration, is
automatic under the 1985 Gramm-Rudman Act that was designed to
force the president and Congress to reduce the federal deficit.
This year, Congress and the administration failed to find a
compromise.
   ``I think it may be that sequester is the best available
alternative. At least it is real,'' said Richard Darman, director
of the White House Office of Management and Budget.
   The automatic budget cuts of Gramm-Rudman took effect in 1986
and 1987 as well, but Congress acted quickly to restore the lost
funds, a process that Darman called ``phony.''
   ``This time, if it goes into effect, I think it would be good if
people would live with it and say, `don't restore the cuts,'''
Darman said on the ABC-TV program, ``This Week With David
Brinkley.''
   The chairman of the House Budget Committee, Rep. Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., said he thought Congress and President Bush could agree
on a formula similar to a Senate package passed last Friday that
met the Gramm-Rudman targets.
   The failure to meet those targets, said Panetta, was linked to
the sharp drop in stock prices Friday.
   ``I think there is a relationship because I think that for the
last eight to 10 years, we've been essentially on a debt binge in
this country,'' Panetta said on the NBC-TV program ``Meet the
Press.''
   The federal debt has reached $3.1 trillion, and corporate and
personal debt also have soared, he said.
   ``In Washington ... we've reached a point where we simply don't
have strong leadership to try to reduce the deficit and make tough
choices,'' he said.
   An author of the Gramm-Rudman law, Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas,
rebutted criticism by some members of Congress that the bill had
led the government to engage in deceptive accounting practices and
had exacerbated the deficit.
   ``The bottom line is, under Gramm-Rudman, we've cut the deficit
in half. We've cut the rate of growth in federal spending in half.
And the federal government has gotten smaller relative to the
private sector of the economy,'' he said.
   ``Has the Congress cheated? And has the president, in the best
spirit of bipartisanship, worked with Congress to cheat? The answer
is yes,'' said Gramm. ``But are we better off with Gramm-Rudman
than we would be without it? I think the answer is, clearly, yes.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
