<FIRST>r a AM-AmmoniaLeak 1stLd-Writethru a0740 10-15 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ammonia Leak, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0740,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Evacuated and Four Hospitalized After Ammonia Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 11th, `Elderly people...,' to give details
on where evacuees were sent.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLSTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ammonia leak at a pizza plant prompted
the all-night evacuation of this entire town of 6,500 people and
left four people hospitalized Sunday, authorities said.
   An evacuation order was lifted shortly after 5:00 a.m. Sunday
morning, said Wellston Assistant Fire Chief Bob Long.
   ``We had some fog that moved in last night _ it was keeping the
ammonia smell around parts of town,'' Long said. ``The sun dried it
up.''
   Deadly anhydrous ammonia used for refrigeration at the Pillsbury
Co. Jenno's plant began leaking about 8 p.m. Saturday when a
compressor cap blew off a 16-inch pipe inside the plant, said Mayor
John Carey. The evacuation of the town was ordered at 10:30 p.m.
and the leak was contained by 11 p.m.
   About 50 people were taken to area hospitals Saturday night and
early Sunday. Most were given oxygen treatments and released, said
Vinton County Deputy Sheriff Marc Smith on Sunday. Dozens of other
residents were given oxygen treatment by emergency medical units
and paramedics Saturday night.
   ``They all wanted to know if their lungs were going to blow
up,'' Smith said. ``They slept everywhere last night, in their
cars, they were all over the place.''
   Mike Dalton, spill unit supervisor of the Ohio Environmental
Protection Agency, said EPA and plant officials did not immediately
know how much ammonia escaped or how much was in the system.
   ``Once the plant has made the repairs, then they'll recharge and
determine how much they lost,'' Dalton said.
   Wellston policeman Marvin Bates, 26, and Jeno's employee Evelyn
Gilliland, 39, were in fair condition at Holtzer Medical Center,
said a nursing supervisor who did not give her name.
   Ronnie Russell, 27, and William Fisher, 36, were also in fair
condition at Oak Hill Community Hospital, said nursing supervisor
Betty McFann.
   Elderly people and nursing home residents were advised not to
return until later Sunday morning to give the cloud time to
dissipate completely, Long said. Residents of the town's two
nursing homes, Edgewood Manor and the Jenkins Memorial Health
Center, were returned to the homes by about 9 a.m. Sunday, he said.
   Evacuees were taken by school bus to two schools in the nearby
towns of Hamden and McArthur and to a community center in McArthur,
said Ethel Gussler, a dispatcher at the Vinton County sheriff's
department.
   Police and sheriff's deputies said no looting was reported
following the evacuation.
   Employees from Jeno's sanitation division returned to work early
Sunday, Dalton said. The plant manufactures frozen pizzas.
   Environmental damage from the leak appeared to be minimal, he
said. Inspectors had feared that the ammonia would dissolve into
water in streams, storm drains and sanitary sewers. Dalton said
ammonia can kill fish and the bacteria used at sewage treatment
plants to break down raw sewage.
   Runoff from the plant was contained in a diversion ditch around
the plant and did not reach streams, he said.
   ``Anhydrous ammonia reacts with liquid in your lungs, changes
form, then attacks tissues. It can directly suffocate you,'' Dalton
said.
   Wellston is about 90 miles southeast of Columbus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
