<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   10-15 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0698,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with Shamir aide saying talks should be a lower level
but not necessarily in Israel, 3-year-old dying from bullet wound, soldier
sentenced for killing two Palestinians. EDITS to trim; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underground leaders of the Arab uprising on
Sunday rejected a U.S. plan to arrange talks between Israelis and
Palestinians, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir opposed the idea of
holding such talks in Cairo.
   Shamir said he preferred lower-level talks than those proposed
by the United States and that they should be held in Israel.
   Security forces killed a Palestinian and wounded three others
during protests in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and Arab
reports said a Palestinian accused of collaborating with Israel was
killed by masked activists.
   The latest deaths brought to 595 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israeli soldiers and civilians during the 22-month-old
uprising; another 130 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs
as suspected collaborators. Forty Israelis also have died in the
violence.
   A U.S. plan formulated by Secretary of State James A. Baker III
is designed to bring about a meeting in Cairo urged by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak as a way to bridge differences between
Israel and the PLO.
   The underground Palestinian leadership, in its 47th leaflet
since the start of the rebellion in December 1987, said it
``rejects America's suspicious role, primarily James Baker's five
points.''
   Baker's plan calls for consultations between the Israeli and
Egyptian foreign ministers to agree on the makeup of a Palestinian
delegation for the proposed Cairo meeting.
   Mubarak urged the meeting as a way to revive Israel's stalled
peace initiative, which calls for elections among Palestinians in
the West Bank and Gaza to pick delegates to negotiate with Israel
on interim self-rule.
   The leaflet from the uprising's PLO-backed leadership said
Baker's ideas merely supported Shamir's election plan and were a
way to avoid the international peace conference that the PLO wants.
The uprising leaders already have rejected the Shamir plan.
   In an interview with the independent daily Maariv, Shamir said
he saw no reason to meet in Cairo.
   ``Why go to Cairo, when the two sides, Israeli and Palestinian,
are here?'' Shamir asked.
   He said the meeting should be in Israel and that it should
merely be a gathering of technocrats to iron out details of his
election plan.
   Shamir aide Avi Pazner later said the prime minister did not
mean that such talks could only be held in Israel but was ``just
raising different possibilites.''
   But he said Shamir does wants to lower the profile of the
contacts.
   ``You cannot conduct high-level meetings in the limelight
because it is difficult to get results,'' Pazner said.
   Also Sunday, a military court sentenced a reserve soldier to two
years in prison for causing the death of two Palestinians in May
1988, the army said.
   Army raido said Ilan Orev, 25, was chasing stone-throwers in the
West Bank village of Bani Naim when he knelt, took aim and fired
two bullets into the heads of two rioters, in violation of orders
not to open fire.
   Late Sunday, 3-year-old Attiyah el-Ghurani of the Shati refugee
camp died of a gunshot injury he suffered on Thursday, the army
said.
   Officials at Shifa hospital in Gaza said the boy's skull had
been shattered by a rubber-coated metal pellet fired by Israeli
soldiers.
   The army said at the time that its troops had not opened fire in
the area but that it was checking further. An army spokesman said
Sunday that no new details were available.
</TEXT>
