<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 1950EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AbortionProtests     10-15 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abortion Protests,0609</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March for Abortion Rights In San Francisco, New Jersey</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of abortion-rights
supporters, buoyed by recent legal and political victories, marched
through downtown San Francisco to a rally in front of City Hall on
Sunday.
   Across the continent in Trenton, N.J., several thousand
demonstrators chanted, waved banners and marched on the Statehouse
to tell lawmakers not to tamper with their right to a safe and
legal abortion.
   The San Francisco marchers, about three-fourths of them women,
carried signs proclaiming the right to choose abortion and, in some
cases, denouncing President Bush for his anti-abortion stand.
   ``A lot of the younger generation felt the right was safe, but
now it's threatened,'' said Alice Wallace, 70, of San Francisco,
who wore a ``Retain Choice!'' sign on her back. ``I think the
politicians will be hearing it.''
   Police estimated the crowd at 30,000. March coordinator Jessica
Braverman said the turnout was 45,000 to 60,000. No anti-abortion
demonstrators were seen along the route.
   After parading past friendly onlookers along more than a mile of
Market Street, the city's main boulevard, marchers gathered in
front of City Hall for a rally and speeches by politicians.
   Some of the loudest cheers were for Norma McCorvey, the Texas
woman who was ``Jane Roe'' in the 1973 Supreme Court ruling
legalizing abortion.
   The march, organized by California's National Organization for
Women Chapter and the Bay Area Pro-Choice Coalition, came on the
heels of several developments favorable to the abortion-rights
cause around the nation.
   Last week Congress, for the first time since 1981, voted to fund
Medicaid abortions for poor women in cases of rape and incest,
despite a veto threat by Bush. Earlier in the week the Florida
Legislature rejected attempts by Gov. Bob Martinez to tighten
restrictions on abortion.
   The Florida Supreme Court and a California Court of Appeal have
blocked enforcement this month of state laws that would require
parental consent for minors' abortions. And Democratic candidates
for governor in Virginia and New Jersey have used their
abortion-rights stands to gain on their Republican opponents,
according to opinion polls.
   Also on Sunday, Vermont Gov. Madeleine M. Kunin in Washington
unveiled an unusual plea to the Supreme Court from 10 governors
urging the justices to reject efforts to restrict abortions.
   A number of San Francisco marchers said a recent Supreme Court
ruling giving states more authority to restrict abortion had
galvanized pro-choice sentiment.
   ``People didn't think their right to choose was threatened. Now,
with the Webster (Supreme Court) ruling, they're aware of the
threat,'' said Lita Krowech of Oakland, whose T-shirt read, ``U.S.
Out of My Uterus.''
   Several signs called for U.S. approval of RU-486, the French
abortion-inducing pill.
   The New Jersey gathering Sunday drew about 6,500, state police
estimated. Rally organizers said 10,000 people participated.
   Demonstrators filled the street in front of the Statehouse and
drew national women's rights leaders, who said the nation is
watching the New Jersey governor's race. They told the crowd that
lawmakers will begin chipping away at abortion rights unless
pro-choice voices are heard in every state.
   ``You will set the standard for the 1990s. You will prove to
candidates across the country _ if you're out of touch, you could
be out of office,'' said Kate Michelman, executive director of the
National Abortion Rights Action League.
   Anti-abortion forces staged a small demonstration about a block
away. On Saturday, 116 people were arrested in Chicago and 69 in
Boston during anti-abortion demonstrations outside clinics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
