<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 2036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Wallenberg     10-15 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Wallenberg,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wallenberg's Siblings Arrive in Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of Raoul Wallenberg planned to meet
Monday with Soviet officials in hopes of learning the fate of the
Swede who saved tens of thousands of Hungarian Jews from Nazi
extermination, then vanished after Soviet troops arrested him in
1945.
   Wallenberg's half-sister Nina Lagergren and half-brother Guy von
Dardel arrived in Moscow Sunday. They were accompanied by the
chairman and the secretary of the Stockholm-based Raoul Wallenberg
Association, retired diplomat Per Anger and Sonja Sonnefeld.
   They dined Sunday night at the Swedish Embassy in Moscow, an
embassy spokesman said.
   The group was to meet Monday with Deputy Foreign Secretary V.
Nikiforov and deputy chairman of the KGB, V. Pirozhkov. They also
will examine Soviet files on Wallenberg.
   The Soviets say files discovered in 1957 showed that Wallenberg
died of natural causes in prison 10 years earlier.
   But numerous accounts over the years from other prisoners
indicate he was alive in Soviet prisons and labor camps long after
the official report of his death. If alive, he would be 77 years
old.
   On Sunday, the newspaper Komsomolskaya Pravda published an
interview with an official of the Butyrskaya Prison who said that
prison records show Wallenberg was not held there between 1972 and
1980. A man named Yan Kaplan reported he had seen Wallenberg in the
prison hospital in 1975.
</TEXT>
