<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     10-15 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Minister Nominated For President By Opposition Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hungary-Communists, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reform group once controlled by the
now-defunct Communist Party on Sunday nominated Justice Minister
Kalman Kulcsar to run for president, officials said.
   The Patriotic People's Front, made up of union, youth, women's
and other groups, also elected the 61-year-old Kulcsar as chairman
at a two-day congress that ended Sunday. He has been at the
forefront of democratic reform in Hungary.
   The presidential election, tentatively set for Nov. 25, would be
the country's first free national balloting in 41 years.
Legislative elections are promised by June next year.
   Kulcsar is the fourth candidate to be nominated for president,
after Imre Pozsgay, the country's best known reformer, Zoltan
Kiraly of the Social Democratic Party and Sandor Racz.
   Racz was nominated last month by a small fringe group named the
Hungarian October Party, which says it wants to realize the goals
of the 1956 anti-Stalinist uprising.
   Pozsgay was nominated for president in June by the Communist
Party, which renamed itself the Hungarian Socialist Party last
weekend at a historic party congress that pledged to work for
democratic reforms.
   The new office of president is expected to be created this week
when Parliament takes up proposed legislation.
   Under the proposed bill, parties and individuals could put up a
candidate provided they acquire 50,000 signatures and deliver them
to the national electoral committee 20 days before the balloting.
   The election for the presidency is tentatively set for Nov. 25.
The new office will replace the current largely ceremonial post of
``president of the presidential council'' held by Bruno F. Straub.
   Under proposed constitutional changes, the office of president
would be vested with much greater powers than the post. Pozsgay has
said the new president should not be able to hold any party job.
</TEXT>
