<FIRST>r a AM-Galveston-1900Hurricane     10-15 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Galveston-1900 Hurricane,0167</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hurricane in 1900 Killed More Than 6,000 in Galveston</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Storm Jerry, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Galveston Island, a barrier coast off the Texas coast, was
struck by the deadliest hurricane on record in September 1900.
   The powerful storm sent a wall of water washing over the island,
and some called it the worst natural disaster in U.S. history.
   The death toll from that storm isn't certain, but experts
generally agree it easily topped 6,000. Some accounts placed the
number of people killed at 8,000.
   The storm caused damage estimated at $30 million and $40 million.
   Fifteen years later, in August, another hurricane hit Galveston.
The official death toll was estimated at 275, much lower than the
great 1900 storm.
   That's because storm-wary residents had raised the grade of the
island and built a seawall to protect them from surging tides
blamed for most of the deaths. Still, damage from the 1915 storm
was set at $50 million.
</TEXT>
