<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 2159EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Dance     10-15 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Graham Dancers as Choreographers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   During this season of the Martha Graham Dance
Company, short dances by some of the company members are being
shown. Even on those programs, most of the evening has dances
created by Miss Graham, who is 95.
   The more interesting of the ``Martha and ... New
Choreographers'' programs this past week at the City Center had
Steve Rooks dancing his own solo, a love duet choreographed by
Jacqulyn Buglisi and Maxine Sherman doing her own abstract solo.
   Rooks' solo, ``Outside,'' has a text from the gospel of Matthew
printed in the program so the audience knew what he was driving at.
Rooks also conveyed it clearly in his dance. There was not only
weeping and gnashing of teeth but fear, flight _ which he managed
to suggest by flinging himself in circles instead of running,
supplication as humble as a dog's begging and despair. It was a
tour de force.
   Joyce Herring and Donlin Foreman danced ``Sospiri,'' which was
totally a beautiful love duet. It included, at different times, a
spiritual sense and graphic embraces.
   Program notes for Maxine Sherman's ``Watermark'' say that the
mystery and virtue of fidelity will unfold. Miss Sherman was more
abstract than that. Her green chiffon and long hair unfolded but we
received no message.
   In the earlier program, Thea Nerissa Barnes danced excerpts from
her own ``Portrait.'' This was inspired by her grandmother. A
rather well-known solo, ``Cry,'' dedicated ``to all our mothers
everywhere,'' performed at the Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater,
is similar and more telling, which detracted a bit from the impact
of ``Portrait.''
   Camille Brown and Young-Ha Yoo danced Lyndon Branaugh's
``Dissonant Conversation.'' It's interesting but looks the most
closely patterned on Graham movement style, as backs arch and necks
bend and hold, like sculpture. The woman pushes the man a couple of
times. She approaches him from the side, as his arm is extended so
that his arm is around her. At the end, they've traded the still
positions in which they began.
   Each program ended with an important Graham work, ``Cortege of
Eagles'' from 1967 and ``The Rite of Spring'' from 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
