<FIRST>r a AM-MarcosEntombment     10-15 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos Entombment,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Attend Marcos Entombment; Former Chief Justice Collapses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people braved wilting heat Sunday
to see Ferdinand Marcos laid ``temporarily to rest'' in a service
that was part religious ceremony and part political rally.
   Enrique Fernando, the last Philippine Supreme Court Chief
Justice during Marcos' rule, collapsed during an emotional speech
by the ousted Philippine president's son, Ferdinand Jr. or ``Bong
Bong.''
   Dr. Azucena Ignacio, Marcos' personal physician, rushed from the
raised platform holding Marcos' coffin and attended to Fernando
before an ambulance whisked him to St. Francis Medical Center. He
was listed in stable condition.
   Marcos died at the same hospital Sept. 28 at age 72 after a long
illness.
   Initial ambulance reports said the 74-year-old Fernando, who
reportedly has a slight heart ailment, had succumbed to the heat,
exacerbated by the crush of people. The temperature at the cemetery
was about 83 degrees with 72 percent humidity, the National Weather
Service said.
   More than 2,500 people waited hours for Marcos' widow, Imelda,
to arrive at the Valley of the Temples Memorial Park with her
husband's body.
   The funeral procession began shortly after 11:15 a.m. when more
than a dozen men rolled Marcos' casket up a long, winding hillside
drive, with hundreds of mourners walking behind.
   They were preceded by supporters carrying the presidential seal
of the Philippines and U.S. and Philippine flags.
   When the pallbearers reached the stairs leading to the small
air-conditioned mausoleum, which had the initials FM landscaped
into shrubs below, elderly retired Philippine generals were
replaced by younger men.
   Once up the stairs, the closed coffin, covered with a Philippine
flag, was surrounded by white flowers on a porch overlooking the
mourners below.
   Mrs. Marcos, dressed all in black, was joined on the platform by
her son, daughter, Irene Araneta, and adopted daughter, Aimee
Marcos.
   There were prayers and a blessing by Monsignor Domingo Nebres,
the Philippine priest who drew the wrath of the Honolulu Catholic
Diocese for comparing Marcos to Jesus Christ during a funeral Mass
Friday.
   Ms. Araneta sang her father's favorite long song and Mrs. Marcos
sang ``Ave Maria'' and the Lord's Prayer.
   Eleven-year-old Aimee Marcos read a saying ``Daddy, I will
always love you forever. Thank you for your legacy of love.''
   The service took a more political turn after pop star Imelda
Papin, Mrs. Marcos' partner in a recent commercial recording duet,
sang a rousing rendition of the Philippine national anthem, with
many in the crowd singing along.
   Bong-Bong Marcos, widely reported to have political aspirations
himself, stirred the crowd with a eulogy to his father, whom he
called ``a man of unbridled excellence.''
   Mrs. Marcos has vowed to eventually bury her husband in the
Philippines and said entombing him above ground in the mausoleum
would make it easier to return his remains to his homeland.
   Philippine President Corazon Aquino, who replaced Marcos after a
1986 popular revolt ended his 20-year dictatorial rule and sent him
into exile here, has prohibited Marcos' return even in death.
   The Marcoses were subsequently indicted on U.S. criminal
racketeering charges accusing of them of looting their homeland's
treasury.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
