<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 2306EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-MarketScene     10-15 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Market Scene,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Investors Calm Despite Wall Street Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investors Monday were visibly calmer about
the stock market than they were after Black Monday two years ago.
   A retail brokerage office of the giant Nomura Securities Co. in
the central Ginza district was somewhat busier than a usual Monday
morning, but the market players seemed to be waiting for bargains
rather than unloading their shares in a panic.
   ``I expect the Nikkei index to remain bearish all day, but I am
not so worried because we all know it is due to external factors,''
said an investor watching the key index shortly after the market
opening.
   ``I am going to sit and wait for a while and start buying shares
later on as shares start hitting the bottom,'' he said.
   In October 1987, after a plunge on Wall Street that went down in
history as Black Monday, brokerages in Tokyo were packed with
massive sell orders that led to the Black Tuesday here.
   The Nikkei average fell 3,836 points, or about 15 percent, on
Oct. 20, 1987, following a 23 percent plunge on Wall Street,
largely due to panic selling by private investors.
   ``Japanese private investors seemed to have learned the lesson
that fluctuation of the Wall Street index is only one of many
aspects of the Tokyo market,'' said a dealer at Nikko Securities
Co., speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It is undoubtedly an
important elmement, but not necessarily as dominant as it was
thought to be.''
   Keiishi Nishida, a dealer at the Tokyo office of Kidder Peabody
Securities Co., said: ``This is nothing like the crash two years
ago when private investors rushed to the brokers from early in the
morning and sold all they had. I don't think any investors expect
Tokyo shares to drop like New York this time.''
   But he added that investors remained hesitant to place buy
orders because ``they want to make sure that the New York plunge
was only a one-time thing, and the Dow Jones will not go down
further Monday there.''
   Nishida also attributed Tokyo's moderate recovery in late
morning to programmed trading.
   ``After the sizable drop, buy orders from institutional
investors on program-trading came in,'' he said. ``But other than
that, I don't expect much of buy orders today.''
   Another investor in the Ginza office commented: ``In a trading
day like today, you must deal with caution.''
</TEXT>
