<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-MutualFunds 1stLd-Writethru   10-15 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Mutual Funds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Redemptions Running `Light' At Nation's Biggest Stock Fund</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT week's decline to 216 points sted 226</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the nation's largest stock mutual
fund said redemption requests have been running ``very light''
since Friday's market scare partly because investors are in for the
long haul and aren't necessarily spooked by even a large decline.
   Following last week's 216-point decline in the Dow Jones
industrial average, most of which hit during the last hour of
trading Friday, some market observers voiced fears that mutual
funds would be hit with massive redemptions by clients wanting to
get out of the market.
   That could force fund managers to dump stocks in order to raise
enough cash to pay their clients, thereby exacerbating the market
turmoil.
   But money market guru Peter Lynch, who heads Fidelity
Investments' $12.5 billion Magellan fund, said Sunday that ``the
real fast, aggressive people left before the close on Friday. This
weekend (redemptions have) been very light.''
   Lynch admits that over the past six weeks he has increased
Magellan's cash position by $350 million to $850 million, but it
was not because he feared his fund's shareholders would start
cashing out. Rather, he said in a telephone interview from his
Boston home, ``I haven't been finding that many stocks that are
undervalued.''
   Investors generally view stock funds as long-term investments
and aren't likely to ``rush out and redeem that quickly,'' said
Erick Kanter, vice president of the Investment Company Institute, a
Washington-based trade association of mutual funds.
   Stock funds account for roughly 25 percent of total mutual fund
assets of $242 billion. Most stock funds keep about 10 percent of
their total assets in cash.
   A Gallup survey of 150 Fidelity customers late Friday and early
Saturday found that 84 percent said they had invested for the long
term while 4 percent said they intended to sell their fund shares
in the next few weeks.
   Kanter said that even following Black Monday, Oct. 19, 1987,
when the Dow plummeted 508 points, only 2 percent of total stock
fund assets actually were redeemed.
   Those who did redeem ``wound up losing a lot because stock funds
rebounded very quickly,'' Kanter said. Even Magellan posted a gain
at the close of 1987, although it was a 1 percent increase rather
than the 41 percent gain that the fund had been tracking before
Black Monday.
   Still, Lynch said Magellan has had ``redemptions up until
August. ... The public has been very nervous since '87 and has been
cutting back pretty steadily.''
   Lynch said he believed the overall stock market likely would
have a net gain for the full year, making 1989 the record-setting
eighth consecutive advancing year.
   ``The reason we've had eight straight years is because we had 16
years of nothing,'' he said. ``The market went sideways or down for
16 years.''
   The previous longest advance began in 1896 and lasted for six
years, Lynch said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
