<FIRST>u f AM-Israel-Market 1stLd-Writethru   10-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Market, 1st Ld-Writethru,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tel Aviv Stock Exchange Dives 6.9 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 1st 2 graphs to CORRECT market not first to open; ADDS
other market notes; uppicks 3rd graf pvs: ``What is ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's stock exchange, one of the few foreign
markets to trade on the weekend after the Wall Street plunge,
witnessed frantic trading and a 6.9 percent drop in share value
Sunday, officials said.
   Although the Tel Aviv market is small and limited to local
stocks, analysts looked to the exchange for signs of how other
world markets would react. Among a handful of small foreign markets
to trade over the weekend, Taiwan lost ground but South Korea
posted a small gain.
   ``What is happening here is a reaction to the news coming from
New York on Friday,'' said Yossi Nitzani, director of the stock
exchange. ``There are large amounts of selling in almost all areas
of the market.
   ``The feeling here is that something very significant happened
in New York,'' Nitzani said. ``Capital markets don't like
uncertainty, so the first reaction was to get out and wait for
things to become clearer.''
   Trading was three times its usual volume, with stocks declining
in paper value by $400 million, Nitzani said in an interview. It
was the sharpest fall since October 1987, when Israeli share values
were off 8.5 percent in reaction to the New York crash.
   Sunday's fall in the dollar-linked bond market was less
dramatic, down 2 percent.
   No U.S. stocks are traded in Israel and no Israeli stocks are
sold on Wall Street, but the U.S. market has strong influence in
Israel because the two economies are closely intertwined.
   The Tel Aviv exchange is open from Sunday to Thursday and closed
Friday and Saturday for the Jewish sabbath.
   Simcha Sadan, an economist at Tel Aviv University, said on
Israel Television there could be a spillover into Israel because of
extensive economic ties between Israel and the United States, its
major ally and source of nearly $3 billion in annual aid.
   ``If the American economy gets sick, then we will certainly get
pneumonia,'' he said.
   The director of one of Tel Aviv's largest trading houses
predicted further drops after London and Tokyo openend.
   ``I am afraid it is not finished,'' he said, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``London will probably fall when it opens
Monday and that will influence people here as well as in New York.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
