<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 2004EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-VendingInnovations 1stLd-Writethru f0021 10-15 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vending Innovations, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0021,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Vending Machines Offer Cappuccino, Hot Pizzas and Frozen Dinners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT spelling of ``espresso,'' sted ``expresso.''
SUBS 6th graf, `We use ...,' to CORRECT spelling of Feitshans. A version
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vending machines have come a long way from
bubble-gum machines and coffee, soda and candy dispensers. Now a
machine will sell you hot, personal-size pizzas, or a fresh cup of
cappuccino or espresso coffee.
   These and other innovations _ along with coinless ``debit card''
machines _ were introduced over the weekend at the annual
convention of the National Automatic Merchandising Association.
   The trade show drew thousands of representatives of the $20.9
billion vending machine industry, association spokesman David Stone
said Sunday.
   The upscale coffee machines, manufactured by the Italian
corporation Borghi SpA, crush a small amount of coffee beans for
each cup, blast steam through the grounds, and dispense a strong,
tasty brew in a tiny cup.
   ``We're looking for the upscale, higher-end consumers who
appreciate a better, European cup of coffee and ethnic groups who
don't like American coffee because they find it too diluted,'' said
Erick Feitshans, director of U.S. operations for Borghi.
   ``We use a filter ... that de-chlorinates and purifies the
water,'' said Feitshans, who noted there is an industry trend
toward using filtered water ``so we don't use dirt water out of
city plumbing systems.''
   The machines also make hot chocolate and regular, American-style
coffee for consumers with more conventional tastes.
   Coffee costs from 80 cents to $1.20, with cappuccino the
costliest.
   Pennsylvania businessman G.W. Black and his son, Brett, offered
a 7-inch cheese and pepperoni pizza that takes 60 seconds to make
in their Pizza Chef, a microwave-pizza oven. They hope the $2 tab
for a pie will be within the budget of college students looking for
a late-night snack.
   ``It's a little bigger than a pan pizza at Pizza Hut and it's a
buck cheaper,'' Black said. ``It's not doughy and it's not super
crispy. I think we did a good job ... for a microwave pizza.''
   Bert de Vos, owner of De Vos International, a vending machine
company in the Netherlands, displayed his ``Deepfrozen'' machine
that sells a consumer a frozen dinner and has a built-in microwave
oven to heat it up.
   To make it easier for customers to pay for these items, vendors
are moving toward introducing debit card systems, especially on
college campuses, Stone said.
   Customers can feed bills, such as $10, into a machine which
produces a magnetic-strip credit card. When the card is inserted
into a vending machine to buy an item like a 50-cent candy bar, the
purchase price is automatically deducted, leaving $9.50 on the card.
   Students at the University of Kentucky are already using the
debit cards for the campus cafeteria, vending machines and even
washing machines, said Bruce Vernon, customer service manager for
Debitek, based in Chattanooga, Tenn., which makes one of the debit
card models.
   ``And it's much easier for the vending industry,'' he said. ``It
takes all the coin mechanisms out of the machine,'' which cuts the
maintenance costs for collecting money and unjamming slots.
   ``It (the technology) is here already ... but it looks like this
is the year it's going to take off,'' Vernon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
