<FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-89 2133EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-ForeignInvestment Bjt   10-15 0786</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Foreign Investment, Bjt,0809</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japanese Investment Doesn't Threaten America, Experts Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to CORRECT cycle designator.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE KURTENBACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese investment in American real estate and
businesses does not threaten the national security or economic
health of the United States, experts told a conference in Tokyo
last week.
   But strong public resentment over highly publicized Japanese
purchases of American companies, like Sony Corp.'s recent $3.4
billion takeover of Columbia Pictures, indicates Japan should do
more to reassure Americans of its good intentions, they said.
   ``Foreign investment is good for both economies ... as President
John F. Kennedy once said, `a rising tide lifts all the boats,'''
said Elliot Richardson, a former U.S. secretary of both commerce
and defense.
   Aside from helping cover the U.S. trade and federal budget
deficits, Japanese investment can aid technology transfers and help
revitalize U.S. industries through the sharing by Japanese
companies of management and production techniques with American
partners, speakers at the conference said.
   They acknowledged, however, that the perception of Japanese
investment among many Americans was strongly negative and could get
worse.
   ``Americans grew up in an era when the U.S. was the source, not
the recipient, of foreign investment. They feel we are losing
control of our economic destiny,'' said Richardson, who heads the
Washington-based Association for International Investment, a
conference sponsor.
   The American sponsors and their Japanese counterpart, the
Council for Better Corporate Citizenship, said they held the
conference to help the Japanese understand why their investments in
America can be controversial even while the U.S. government
welcomes them.
   In a recent Gallup poll reported in Newsweek magazine, 52
percent of the people polled said they viewed Japanese economic
might as a greater threat than Soviet military power.
   Japanese investment in the United States has come under fire
largely because of its rapid growth _ twice as fast as that of
other nations _ in highly visible areas, U.S. Ambassador to Japan
Michael Armacost told the conference.
   Japan's total investment in American real estate, corporations
and subsidiaries skyrocketed from $4.7 billion in 1980 to $53.4
billion in 1988.
   Of a total $65 billion in foreign direct investment in 1988,
Japan accounted for $14.2 billion, just behind Britain's $21.5
billion. Economists estimate Japanese investment will reach $21
billion this year.
   Highly publicized lawsuits against Japanese firms accusing them
of racial and sexual discrimination along with problems in
balancing American and Japanese management styles and staff in U.S.
offices have contributed to the backlash against Japanese
investment, speakers said.
   Alice Young, a partner in the New York-based law firm Milbank,
Tweed, Hadley and McCloy, urged Japanese investors to keep a low
profile in making investments _ to ``avoid plastering `Japan Inc.'
all over everything'' _ to seek expert advice to avoid lawsuits
over largely avoidable problems, and to hire and promote the best
American talent to positions of responsibility.
   Armacost noted that 85 percent of all chief executive officers
in Japanese overseas subsidiaries are Japanese, while only 20
percent of the CEO positions in overseas subsidiaries in Japan are
filled by expatriates.
   ``Until companies are perceived as creating the best environment
for American workers, you won't get the best,'' Ms. Young said.
   Japanese investors can also allay American anxiety over their
economic activities by getting more deeply involved in community
activities in the United States, speakers said.
   ``A Japanese corporation in America needs to be more responsible
to community concerns than it would be at home,'' said Richardson,
singling out the Hitachi Foundation's program of matching grants to
community projects.
   While there is substantial room for improvement in the way
Japanese firms operate in the United States, there is no evidence
to support charges that Japan is ``buying America on the cheap,''
said Jonathon E. Colby, a partner in Blackstone Financial Services
Inc.
   ``Japanese companies buy only high-quality assets at a fair
price,'' Colby said.
   Japanese companies operating subsidiaries in the United States
are reinvesting their profits from American operations rather than
sending them home, said Samuel M. Rosenblatt, president of the
Association for International Investment.
   The rate of return from U.S. affiliates from 1981 to 1988 was
only 3.3 percent for Japanese-owned firms, compared with 5.6
percent for all foreign-owned firms in the United States,
indicating that Japanese are investing in America for the long
term, he said.
   Officials of the Departments of Commerce and Defense said there
were no signs that Japanese investment was threatening U.S.
national security.
   Robert L. Mullen, deputy undersecretary of defense, said that in
cases in which a joint venture would involve the sole U.S. company
with a strategic product or technology, the Defense Department
makes arrangements to ensure the deal will not compromise national
security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
